<br>
How about this time you take a real look at what you actually spend in real US dollars on taxes.  When I do all the calculations (Fed tax-refund/state tax/property tax/vehicle tax/gas tax/6% on all purchases of my taxed income/profits taken and taxed) I find that my taxed income exceeds 40%.  Now it stands to reason that I'm not taking into consideration other taxes I'm paying, so I'm getting much closer to that 50% in tax burden than not.  <br>
<br>
What's really scary for an average person is when you compute your monthly obligations out including your tax burden.<br>
<br>
~42% Taxes <br>
~$400 in groceries<br>
~$800 car payments<br>
~$1000 for child care<br>
~$400 for pre-school<br>
~$1000 to retirement<br>
~$600 for college<br>
~$800 for insurance<br>
<br>
The biggest flaw in all your argument is using statistical data that gives you percentages as an obligation instead of real dollars.  I personally have zero problem with someone that has figured out how to make $900,000 per year in income and when they pay $150,000 to $300,000 in taxes (keep in mind that most people in this pay group are self-employed so they end up paying double FICA taxes), then I think they have fulfilled their obligation to the rest of us in supporting the government.  <br>
<br>
Our society was supposedly built by rewarding those few people that have the drive and the talent to create or produce.  If you participate in charitable organizations have you ever noticed who is doing the ground work?  It's not other poor schmucks like me, it's those same people that pay the most real dollars in taxes.  Does the high net income person have more time available to him for charity work?  Usually those people are workaholics and they do the charity work because they make the time for it.  My point is instead of giving the government more money to spend frivolously or for their own constituent's interest, take the money back and let us do it ourselves.  Instead of whining about how the less advantaged aren't being taken care of, roll up your sleeves and do something about it...personally.  Hell....I can't say I care at all about someone that won't make any effort at all to improve their condition, but I will sure as hell reach out a hand to someone that cares enough to participate.<br>
<br>
Until the culture changes whereby we think government is our momma and poppa and take responsibility ourselves I guess you're right....taxes will continue to go up, and up, and up.<br>
