<br>
Essentially, by looking at 1992 and 1993 incomes in isolation, Feldstein and Feenberg were able to draw some conclusions about tax that would have been collected in 1993 if no tax increase had been put in place.  What F &amp; F specifically leave out, however, is the overall trend in incomes for wealthy tax payers from 91-95.<br>
<br>
In 1992, Clinton and Congress were widely believed to be on the threshhold of passing a tax increase,specifically to deal with the deficit.  In anticipation of this, some income that would have been paid in 1993, was shifted to the 1992 tax year (through exercise of options, early Wall St bonus pays, etc).  So, while it's certainly true to say that taxable incomes for high income earners fell from 1992-1993, that's only part of the picture.  The reality is that incomes jumped substantially from the 1991-1992 tax year(27%), fell in 1993, and then resumed normal growth patterns thereafter. (<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://gsbwww.uchicago.edu/news/capideas/sum98/goolsbee.htm)">gsbwww.uchicago.edu/news/...lsbee.htm)</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
In short, Feenberg and Feldstein were able to show a one time tax avoidance effect due to anticipated changes in the tax code, whoopee, not exactly news.  You , however, have overblown their conclusions into a long term trend that just isn't there Mith.  Are taxes somewhat inefficient? Sure, people have the ability to game the system. As tax rates increase, the incentive for avoidance behaviors rises with them.  But the statement that more taxes=less revenue, and its converse, has not been proven empirically true for anything other than the very short term. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mithrilleyes>mithrilleyes</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.philbrodieband.com/Slide13.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 620<br> <font color=#333333>(4/26/05 10:23 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=97>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: please</span><hr size=1> &gt;&gt;But the statement that more taxes=less revenue, and its converse, has not been proven empirically true for anything other than the very short term.<br>
<br>
Just quickly, this is not what I said. I said higher tax rates do not ALWAYS raise revenues. If you raised everyone's taxes to 90%, to give you an extreme example, revenues would drop because people would a)stop working at their maximum productive level b)would find ways to evade taxes. This is basically the Laffer curve, which I am sure you know already.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.investopedia.com/terms/l/laffercurve.asp">www.investopedia.com/term...rcurve.asp</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Heritage has a nice paper on it, by the man himself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.heritage.org/Research/Taxes/bg1765.cfm">www.heritage.org/Research...bg1765.cfm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
And if you get interested, read this other (long) paper from an NBER economist, which doesn't fully agree with the Laffer article, but it does in good measure (especially about the Reagan tax cuts).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://gsbwww.uchicago.edu/fac/austan.goolsbee/research/laf.pdf">gsbwww.uchicago.edu/fac/a...ch/laf.pdf</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Some people don't believe in the curve, but most respected economist do. <br>
<br>
&quot;I have called this paper an analytical review of&quot;supply-side economics,&quot; a term associated in the United States with extravagant claims about the effects of changes in the tax structure on capital accumulation. In a sense, the analysis I have reviewed here supports these claims: Under what I view as conservative assumptions, I estimated that eliminating capital income taxation would increase capital stock by about 35 percent.... The supply-side economists, if that is the right term for those whose research I have been discussing, have delivered the largest genuinely free lunch I have seen in 25 years in this business, and I believe we would have a better society if we followed their advice.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://nobelprize.org/economics/laureates/1995/index.html">Robert Lucas</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://ideas.repec.org/a/oup/oxecpp/v42y1990i2p293-316.html">Supply-Side Economics: An Analytical Review</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
Personally I have lived the Laffer curve in action in Spain more than once under our beloved Socialist governments, but that is another story. History and country comparisons have proved the validity of the curve over and over. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.philbrodieband.com/Slide13.JPG" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mithrilleyes>mithrilleyes</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.philbrodieband.com/Slide13.JPG" BORDER=0> at: 4/26/05 10:36 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 1642<br> <font color=#333333>(4/26/05 11:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=98>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: please</span><hr size=1> Fair warning, this response will stray even further into economic wonkery than even I usually tread.<br>
<br>
LOLOLOLOL.  Please, please read the papers you cut, paste and link. From the Goolsbee article you linked:<br>
&quot;As a testable hypothesis, however, the original Laffer curve has not fared well...the public has taken the explosion of budget deficits...as a refutation of the idea. More careful<br>
econometric analysis has not been any more supportive.&quot; <br>
<br>
From the author's conclusion in that same paper:<br>
&quot;The notion that governments could raise more money by cutting rates is, indeed, a glorious idea.<br>
It would permit a Pareto improvement of the most enjoyable kind. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Unfortunately for all of us, the data<br>
from the historical record suggest that it is unlikely to be true at anything like today’s marginal tax rates.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
It seems that, for now at least, we will have to keep paying for our tax cuts the old fashioned way.<br>
<br>
The Laffer Curve is viewed as utterly refuted by most economists.  Econometric analysis simply doesn't bear it out, and indeed, such analysis was not part of the curve's conception. Laffer theorized that there *might* be such a curve.  If the folklore is true, he drew it on a napkin over dinner with a colleague.  As pretty pictures help tell stories (even untrue ones) to voters, Americans were flimflammed with it.  If you like, I can walk you through Goolsbee's analysis, as well as the mile high view of what, exactly, econometric analysis involves, and why that methodology is powerful in testing economic hypotheses.<br>
<br>
Further, Goolsbee says:&quot;Using the same methods that NTR authors have used for the 1980s, the elasticities of taxable income calculated for other tax changes seem to be much more modest with several indistinguishable from zero.&quot;<br>
<br>
Essentially Laffer postulates that income is elastic (meaning it has a negative correlative response) with respect to tax rates.  Laffer postulates the existence of some curve representing some point at which the incentive for avoidance is so large, that tax increases lose revenues.  Goolsbee's work, using F&amp;F's own methodology, shows that for most periods, the historical records of the government would indicate this elasticity to be much less than unitary(meaning less than one).   Income elasticity at any point in the income spectrum would only produce the kind of effects Mith describes (losing revenue with an increase) if it were greater than one.  So, for increases in the tax rate, you'll lose *more* {damn typos}revenue to tax inefficiency than the amount of the increase itself. <br>
<br>
Thanks for the laugh.  The usual mis-read, mis-applied horse-puckey. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bumraz@ascension10244>Bumraz</A> at: 4/26/05 3:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vanessalynnerz>VanessalynneRZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 414<br> <font color=#333333>(4/26/05 4:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=99>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: please</span><hr size=1> In this instance I have to agree with Bumraz on about 90% of what's going on here.  All of this budget mumbo-jumbo is trash.  The estate tax is a tax that hits the government directly, so you can stop the economic theory in this one.  <br>
<br>
The primary crux of Bumraz's statements are that Bush is pandering to the rich, which he is.  There are hundreds of thousands of important issues in our day and age, and he's clearly picking the ones to support the prime revenue generators.  I personally have no problem wit this, but from a socally minded standpoint it's wrong, especially at this point in time.  Our economy is going to be a trainwreck in the very near future, and sadly it's going to take an extreme democratic congress to pass a bunch of bullshit laws to balance out all these bullshit republican ones.  I wish that we could have an honest, fiscally minded congress who just tried to do what's right for the country...I'm not holding my breath...<br>
<br>
The one thing I can firmly side with Kura/Dae on is that &quot;death tax&quot; is exactly that.  You die, you pay.  End of story.  And while the beneficiaries of the estate are the ones who pay those charges, estates almost always have to be liquidated, in part or in whole, to pay those taxes.  Then the inheritants end up with a stack of cash, no doubt, but they do frequently lose the family farm.  <br>
<br>
Land is the hardest, and in rural communities it happens well over half the time Bumraz.  I'm a community banker in a VERY rural area.  I've seen lots of family farms come up for auction for that very reason.  You're statement that this only effects the rich isn't fair.  The last few times I've seen this happen was with average farmers, who spent their entire lives amassing land &amp; equipment, then they die suddenly and given that the land is usually partially mortgaged, for the benefit of equipment purchase, there is -0- liquid cash in the estate, and once the estate tax kicks in it's been 40%, and that was AFTER the last estate tax cut.  I can't personally remember what was paid before that, but my grandfather died in 1989 and paid ~42% tax on his estate.  Luckily he had planned a little ahead and had some whole life insurance along with successful children in their own rite, but a family farmer who's kids either work the farm or work a lower middle class job can't even think about shouldering that tax load.  The estate tax is wrong, and while some multi-billionaires will benefit, those are a vastly small portion and they generate plenty of sales/luxury tax on their own, along with their spoiled-Paris Hilton-esque children.  You watch, Paris will end up in BR after her parents are gone.  That's Darwin's law in a financial environment.  <br>
<br>
Back to the main point of what Bumraz has to say, now is the wrong time to do this.  This should have been changed, but it should have been part of an entire income tax revamp.  As wrong as this tax is, I believe it's just as wrong to change it in this day and age, by itself.  Bumraz's points on the AMT are also dead on the money(no pun intended).  <br>
<br>
My personal opinion on the Estate tax is that it's paid by the successful who die unexpectedly.  There is an annual exlcusion to the gift tax (11k/year) and successful, upper-middle class people use it throughout their entire life to move that money down the line, and if they're like my grandfather, they pass on a sense of financial responsibility with it.  <br>
<br>
Alex <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://p075.ezboard.com/bascension10244.showUserPublicProfile?gid=barmaley>Barmaley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 315<br> <font color=#333333>(4/26/05 8:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://p075.ezboard.com/fascension10244frm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3301.topic&index=100>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: please</span><hr size=1> few question, not that I am a specialist in rural financing, but still.<br>
